xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>23916</fr:anchor><fr:addr>jms-0092</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-0092.xml</fr:route><fr:title><fr:link
type="local"
href="stefaniadamato.xml"
addr="stefaniadamato"
title="Stefania Damato">Stefania Damato</fr:link> on a container model of type theory</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>9</fr:month><fr:day>15</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:meta
name="venue"><fr:link
type="local"
href="yamcats-32.xml"
addr="yamcats-32"
title="Yorkshire and Midlands Category Theory Seminar #32">Yorkshire and Midlands Category Theory Seminar #32</fr:link></fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:link
type="local"
href="stefaniadamato.xml"
addr="stefaniadamato"
title="Stefania Damato">Stefania Damato</fr:link> describes a model of type theory in (generalized) containers, joint work with her PhD supervisor <fr:link
type="local"
href="thorstenaltenkirch.xml"
addr="thorstenaltenkirch"
title="Thorsten Altenkirch">Thorsten Altenkirch</fr:link>. The background of this work is the <fr:link
type="external"
href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1612.02346">prior functorial semantics of QIITs</fr:link> due to <fr:link
type="local"
href="thorstenaltenkirch.xml"
addr="thorstenaltenkirch"
title="Thorsten Altenkirch">Thorsten Altenkirch</fr:link>, Paolo Capriotti, Gabe Dijkstra, Nicolai Kraus, and Fredrik Nordvall Foresberg.</fr:p><fr:p>In that prior work, the universal property of QIITs is described in terms of certain functors having initial algebras, but the question of whether initial algebras in fact exist in usual semantic categories was not satisfactorily dealt with. In the context of ordinary inductive types, presentation by a container is a sufficient notion (i.e. the functor should be polynomial). In this work, <fr:link
type="local"
href="stefaniadamato.xml"
addr="stefaniadamato"
title="Stefania Damato">Stefania Damato</fr:link> and <fr:link
type="local"
href="thorstenaltenkirch.xml"
addr="thorstenaltenkirch"
title="Thorsten Altenkirch">Thorsten Altenkirch</fr:link> have needed to generalize the notion of polynomial in a way that <fr:link
type="local"
href="nicolagambino.xml"
addr="nicolagambino"
title="Nicola Gambino">Nicola Gambino</fr:link> suggested is equivalent to <fr:em>familial representability</fr:em>.</fr:p><fr:p>The motivation for finding a model of type theory in containers is that this is apparently necessary in order to be able to use type theoretic constructs in the signature of a QIIT. I never did fully understand how this relates to the constructs that appear in the constructors of the QIIT once its initial algebra is computed, as these happen in <fr:em>different</fr:em> models of type theory: the QIIT is specified, apparently, in the container model but then the QIIT is <fr:em>used</fr:em> in (e.g.) the <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {Set}]]></fr:tex> model. I chatted with <fr:link
type="local"
href="stefaniadamato.xml"
addr="stefaniadamato"
title="Stefania Damato">Stefania Damato</fr:link> afterward and she offered some helpful answers, but I don’t think I fully understood this point.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
